## AI Coding Tools Work – That’s the Problem

By 2026, most teams use AI coding tools in some form: code completion, chat‑based helpers, test generation, and infra templates. Surveys show they genuinely speed up routine work and help teams ship faster. [web:286][web:288][web:291][web:297][web:294]

But the same data shows deep concerns about long‑term code quality, security vulnerabilities, IP risk, and skill erosion when teams adopt AI without guardrails. [web:291][web:294][web:297]

This isn’t about saying “AI bad.” It’s about using AI the way a good senior uses a junior: helpful, fast, and supervised.

---

## Where AI Helps Most (If You Let It)

Teams report the biggest productivity wins from AI in: [web:286][web:291][web:292][web:297]

- Boilerplate and glue:
  - Wiring handlers, basic CRUD, serializers, DTOs.
- Legacy spelunking:
  - Explaining unfamiliar code, generating quick summaries.
- Test scaffolding:
  - Basic unit tests, fuzzing ideas, fixtures.
- Infra and YAML:
  - Drafting K8s manifests, CI pipelines, Terraform skeletons.

Used here, AI offloads drudge work and frees humans for design, architecture, and risk decisions. [web:291][web:292][web:293][web:297]

The trap is letting it creep into areas you don’t understand, then shipping unread code.

